Review the codex entries below for spoiler safety and report every objection as
a structured FINDING. You report evidence; the engine decides the outcome from
your findings and the codex author decides how to act — so grade each axis
honestly rather than reaching for a verdict.

Each finding names one RULE (below). Set `assessment` to "fail" for an
objective defect or "warn" for a concern. Quote the offending sentence of the
ENTRY'S OWN TEXT (never the conditional list's); for conditional_stated_as_fact,
name in `reason` which CONDITIONAL item the sentence states as fact.

REQUIRED (this is correct, in-world register — never fault an entry for having
it): a diegetic, encyclopedia voice. These read like almanac entries, not
prose, and may restate the entity's established facts freely and in any order.

The rules — all three are objective defects when present:

- conditional_stated_as_fact — the entry states, as fact, something listed
  below as CONDITIONAL for that entity. Assertion means the entry's own
  sentence claims it happened or is true. Touching the same theme, describing
  the entity's relation to an open question, or explicitly posing the question
  ("whether X or Y, the paper does not answer") is NOT assertion — leaving
  fates open is exactly what a spoiler-safe entry does.
- machinery_leakage — the entry names story machinery: a node id (e.g.
  "flag:x", "beat:x"), or the words "flag", "beat", "path", or "arc" used
  mechanically. Ordinary English uses ("a footpath", "her heart beats") are not
  leakage.
- ending_title_named — the entry names an ending title{% if ending_titles %}: {{ ending_titles | join(", ") }}{% else %} (none exist yet — skip){% endif %}.

TASTE IS A WARN, NEVER A FAIL. Register, prose quality, and how much of the base
facts an entry restates are matters of degree, not a rule — grade them "warn" at
most. If your `reason` needs "risks", "potential", "could", or "attempts to", it
is not a high-confidence defect; grade it "warn" or lower the confidence, do not
force it to block.

Set `confidence` to how sure you are the named rule is broken as written by the
quoted sentence: "high" when it plainly is, "low" when you are reaching.

